<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dasa Asks Kohl To Intervene in Saudi Arabia for Orders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703185994 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 7 Mar 94 p 93 </F>
<F P=103> AU0703185994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Begging Letter to the Chancellor"] </F>
  [Text] Chancellor Helmut Kohl is to save an important 
large order for the Daimler-Benz subsidiary Deutsche Aerospace 
(Dasa). Together with their European Airbus partners, the 
Germans want to deliver planes for approximately 10 billion 
German marks to Saudi Arabia. However, U.S. President Bill 
Clinton announced that Saudi Arabia will buy the planes from the 
U.S. companies Boeing and McDonnell Douglas. As a result, Dasa 
Chief Juergen Schrempp sent a begging letter to the chancellors. 
"Since we know that the negotiations in Saudi Arabia have not 
yet been finally concluded," the letter says, Kohl should 
advocate the Europeans' cause. In Dasa alone, almost 1,300 jobs 
have to be abolished by 1997, if the order is lost. "Only a 
personal intervention by yourself," Schrempp wrote in clumsy 
German, could "bring about at least a partial turnaround." The 
chancellor has not yet reacted. He is angry with Schrempp and 
his colleagues. Over the past months, they have repeatedly 
criticized the Federal Government harshly for drastically 
reducing research subsidies for aviation and space flight. 

</TEXT>

