<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Satellite Set Up Between Russian, German Institutes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803124094 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0940 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0803124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Potsdam (DDP/ADN): The first direct satellite link 
in the civilian sector between Brandenburg and Russia went into 
operation today. A 2.5 metre dish in Golm on a building of 
Potsdam University is connected to the Dubna nuclear research 
institute near Moscow. The institute in Dubna will have access 
to international scientific networks via the Potsdam link. The 
Institut fuer ComputerIntegriertes Engineering (CoIn) [Institute 
of computer-integrated engineering] in Potsdam is involved on 
the German side. EuroDATA Berlin, which established the 
communications needs of both sides on behalf of the state of 
Brandenburg, provides the service. Both the Dubna institute and 
the satellite project are supported by the Federal Research 
Ministry. 
  Presently, 64,000 bits per second can be transmitted. 
According to the Brandenburg Transport Ministry, the system is 
to be expanded technically and related systems for links to Kiev 
and Minsk added to it. Scientists will thus gradually have 
better opportunities for exchanging data and pictures, and using 
future systems they will be able to hold video conferences. 

</TEXT>

