<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S.-Japanese Trade Dispute `Relapse' to Intervention </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703151694 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
7 Mar 94 p 15 </F>

<F P=103> AU0703151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Odr." commentary: "Relapse"] </F>
  [Text] The United States and Japan are again on the 
warpath regarding trade policies. The U.S. Administration 
demands exact minimum import quotas for certain U.S. products 
from the Japanese in Tokyo. The Japanese Government rejects 
this. It is understandable that in the long run the United 
States is concerned about the horrendous Japanese trade 
surpluses with their own country. However, it is not convincing 
to claim again and again that the Japanese market is closed. 
Since the European auto industry sold altogether 1.1 million 
vehicles in Japan by the end of last year, the reasons for the 
failure of the U.S. automakers to sell more U.S. cars in Japan 
are to be found elsewhere. One cannot talk of free world trade 
if products that are hard to sell are to be pressed into a 
market in the form of minimum import quotas, as the U.S. 
Administration is trying to do in Japan. At the same time, one 
must not fail to see that every solution to that effect finally 
has to burden suppliers from third countries -- that is, exactly 
the European industry. Minimum import quotas are a bad relapse 
into foreign trade regulated by the state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

