<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Special Rules To Remain for Dual-Use Goods </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703202394 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
7 Mar 94 p 15 </F>

<F P=103> AU0703202394 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Stue." report: "Export Control: Rexrodt for Special </F>
Rules"] 
  [Text] Bonn, 6 March -- After the European Union's 
adoption of an export control regulation for goods than can be 
used both for civilian and military purposes (dual use), special 
German provisions that go beyond the Brussels rules will 
continue to exist. This follows from a letter that FRG 
Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt (Free Democratic Party of 
Germany) wrote to the top economic associations. The 
negotiations on a regulation for dual-use goods in Brussels are 
now entering their final stage, Rexrodt wrote. The partners do 
not support the stringent German export control system, he said. 
  Rexrodt announced that Germany's previous additional rules 
have therefore to be changed. This applies, for example, to 
goods that are not on a control list and are only checked 
because of their use in the military sector. Here the reduction 
of the controls to the few countries that have isolated 
themselves in the international community has to be considered. 
Rexrodt wants to examine whether the controls for services and 
the transfer of sensitive knowledge that are not contained in 
the Brussels regulation are only to be valid for a hard core of 
countries and for products to be more precisely defined. As the 
single market continues, one should be increasingly exacting 
regarding the maintenance of additional national rules. 
  The German economy called for the harmonization of the 
export 
rules for dual-use goods without any national exceptions, so 
that the competitive disadvantages resulting from the strict 
German rules are eliminated. There will not be a general change 
of course on real arms, Rexrodt affirmed. However, the Federal 
Government will soon adopt measures that will make the 
authorizing policy clearer and more predictable for 
international cooperation on the level of enterprises so that 
faster decisions can be expected. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

