<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Criticized for `Escalating Tensions' Over Fish </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0703140694 Paris LE FIGARO (LE FIG-ECO supplement) in 
French 5-6 Mar 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> BR0703140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE FIGARO (LE FIG-ECO supplement) </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Fisheries: American Retaliation </F>
Against France"] 
  [Text] The French Foreign Ministry feels that the United 
States "would be responsible for escalating tensions" if it 
imposed sanctions against France in reaction to measures in the 
fisheries sector which Washington considers to be protectionist. 
  "Our decisions were made in full accordance with the 
applicable Community regulations," the ministry states. "If the 
United States were to take retaliatory measures against France, 
it would be responsible for escalating tensions at the very time 
we are preparing the Marrakesh conference, which will make it 
possible to sign the GATT agreements and create a world trade 
organization. One might wonder whether that was a good signal 
to send," the ministry added. 
  Yesterday, the United States officially threatened France 
that it would take retaliatory measures against it as a result 
of the severe sanitary controls applied by Paris on cargos of 
American fish. 
  The American National Fisheries Institute estimated that 
losses for American fishermen, whose products have been turned 
back by the French health authorities since 5 February, total 
1.2 million francs per week. 
  Agriculture and Fisheries Minister Jean Puech accused the 
United States of exporting fish treated with a chemical 
substance used to retain water, which is illegal in France and 
throughout the European Union. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

