<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Accord Reached for U.S. Experts Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0703142194 Paris LA TRIBUNE DESFOSSES in French 7 Mar 94 p 
4 </F>

<F P=103> BR0703142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LA TRIBUNE DESFOSSES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Marc Deger: "Fish: Storm Warning Averted"] </F>
  [Text] Following various verbal warnings, on Friday [4 
March] the United States threatened France officially with 
commercial retaliation because of the strict health measures 
imposed by Paris on fish imports. Washington is accusing the 
French Government of introducing veiled quotas aimed at allaying 
the anger of Breton fishermen. "False accusations," the Hotel 
Matignon [prime minister's office] retorted, stressing that "if 
the Americans are stepping up the pressure on international 
trade it is to cast doubt on the main achievement of the Uruguay 
Round which their Senate refuses to contemplate: the 
institutionalization of a World Trade Organization." 
  In this affair, the Clinton Administration has acted under 
pressure from the National Fisheries Institute, the shipowners' 
lobby, arguing that Massachusetts fishermen were losing $200,000 
a week because of the restrictions on imports imposed by France. 
And the U.S. Special Trade Representative Mickey Kantor 
threatened to introduce trade sanctions on $100 million of 
French exports, especially cheeses, because they are perishable. 
  In Paris, the Quai d'Orsay [Foreign Ministry] immediately 
issued a warning to Washington, stating that the checks carried 
out by France were "perfectly in line with Community 
regulations." It added that "if the United States took the path 
of retaliatory measures against France, it would be responsible 
for escalating tensions at the very time preparations are under 
way for the Marrakesh conference, which will make it possible to 
sign the GATT agreements and to set up the World Trade 
Organization." 
  According to official French figures, only 27.3 tonnes (out 
of 997) of American fish have been banned since the 
strengthening of border checks purely for public health reasons. 
They were batches "swollen" by chemical additives that retain 
water, which amounts to selling water for the price of fish. 
  Paris and Washington have finally chosen the path of peace. 
Fisheries Minister Jean Puech agreed with Mickey Kantor that a 
team of American experts should examine the French checks. This 
team is expected in Paris today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

