<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Considers New Battalion for Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703175694 Paris AFP in English 1738 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0703175694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 7 (AFP) -- France is considering 
sending a new battalion of 800 troops to Sarajevo to reinforce 
its 2,300 peacekeepers in the Bosnian capital, military sources 
said here Monday [7 March]. 
  France already has more than 6,000 troops under the United 
Nations flag in former Yugoslavia. 
  The battalion would consist of career soldiers, infantry and 
engineers, but the decision to send them is not yet formal, the 
sources said. 
  The decision would be taken in close coordination with 
Britain. A British Government source said London could also send 
significant reinforcements to Bosnia. 
  The reinforcements would enable the UN to put into force 
Security Council Resolution 900 providing for restoration of 
essential public services in Sarajevo, the sources said. 
  Meanwhile Prime Minister Edouard Balladur held a meeting 
Monday with General Betrand de Lapresle, who will replace 
General Jean Cot as commander of UN forces in mid-March. 
  Cot is being relieved at the request of UN Secretary-General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali for publicly demanding authority to order 
air strikes against the Serbs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

