<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-045 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Says Serbs Must Return to Peace Process </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0803122694 Paris AFP in English 1153 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0803122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 8 (AFP) -- French Foreign Minister 
Alain Juppe on Tuesday [8 March] insisted on the need to bring 
the Serbs back into the Bosnian peace process, following talks 
here with visiting Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic. 
  "There will be no stable and durable solution if the Serb 
community is not reinvolved" in the peace process, Juppe said, 
adding that France wanted to help in the move. 
  Silajdzic said he would next visit Moscow and hoped the 
Serbs 
would rejoin the negotiations. "They are not excluded unless 
they exclude themselves," he said. 
  The Bosnian prime minister said he hoped the Russians would 
work for a settlement involving the Serbs. 
  Juppe meanwhile appeared to rule out the idea of French 
reinforcements for UN peacekeepers in Bosnia. "All French 
authorities consider that we cannot go beyond our present 
commitment. We are the first contributors. We have done our 
duty." 
  French military sources said Monday Paris was considering 
strengthening its 2,300 soldiers in Sarajevo with a battalion of 
800 men to help enforce a Security Council resolution that calls 
for restoration of basic services such as water and electricity 
in the Bosnian capital. 
  France has a total of 6,000 peacekeepers in former 
Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

