<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Secretary General Issues Report on Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0803072294 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0500 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0803072294 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali noted that 
the leaders of the two communities in Cyprus should be able to 
lead their proximity talks on the confidence-building measures 
to a successful conclusion within the next few weeks. In a 
report to the UN Security Council, a summary of which REUTER 
news agency reported this morning, Butrus-Ghali also notes that 
the proximity talks can not drag on for long. An agreement in 
Cyprus, he adds, would represent the most significant 
development on the island in two decades and would create a new 
and more positive prospect for the future. However, the 
secretary general warns, the consequences of a failure would 
certainly be very negative. In his report, Butrus-Ghali 
describes as positive the fact that President Glavkos Kliridhis 
and [Turkish Cypriot leader] Rauf Denktas accepted the package 
of confidence-building measures in principle, and that they have 
begun intensive negotiations in Nicosia with his representatives 
on the basis of agreed arrangements to work out ways to 
implement the package. Finally, in his report, Butrus-Ghali 
notes that with the show of the necessary goodwill, leaders of 
the two communities will be able to bring the proximity talks to 
a positive conclusion within a few weeks. 

</TEXT>

