<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delcroix Refuses Addition to Contingent in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0703131894 Antwerp GAZET VAN ANTWERPEN in Dutch 7 Mar 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> BR0703131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Antwerp GAZET VAN ANTWERPEN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Enough Belgians in Bosnia -- </F>
Delcroix Does Not Intend To Increase Contingent of UN Troops"] 
  [Excerpt] Belgian Defense Minister Leo Delcroix does not 
intend to send any more UN troops to Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
According to the minister, the Belgian Army has reached the 
limit of its possibilities. It may well be that UN Secretary 
General Butrus-Ghali has great admiration for the work done by 
the Belgian UN troops in Somalia, Rwanda, Croatia, and Bosnia, 
but other countries also must be approached for once, said the 
minister. 
  The minister was reacting to a report in the British SUNDAY 
TIMES claiming that, once again, Belgium will be asked to 
contribute together with Great Britain, France, and Sweden, 
another 5,000 UN troops for Bosnia. That is roughly half the 
figure requested by General Michael Rose, UN commander in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. He believes these extra troops are 
necessary to maintain the cease-fires in Sarajevo and central 
Bosnia in the long term. Following fierce debates within the 
British Government, London said it would be prepared to send an 
additional 1,200 troops to Bosnia to reinforce the 2,500 British 
troops already there. However, London wants British soldiers to 
be accompanied by UN troops sent by other Western countries. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

