<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Farming Will Need Extra Support After EU Entry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0703160094 Helsinki HUFUVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 7 Mar 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> BR0703160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFUVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Agriculture Needs 2 Billion Extra"] </F>
  [Text] Agriculture will need additional support of almost 
2 billion markkas next year if Finland joins the European Union 
[EU]. This was the assessment given by Foreign Minister Heikki 
Haavisto in Sunday's [6 March] TURUN SANOMAT. 
  According to Haavisto, the transition to the EU's pricing 
system means that the production price of certain products will 
be halved and the value of stockpiled products will fall. 
  According to Haavisto, 3 to 4 billion markkas in national 
agricultural support will be needed after the transitional 
period. This year direct support to agriculture will be 6.5 
billion markkas. 
  In TURUN SANOMAT Haavisto gave concrete figures for the 
additional support that Prime Minister Esko Aho said he believed 
would be necessary in the Eduskunta on Friday. Social 
Democratic circles have already been fairly critical of calls 
for additional support. The matter could also cause conflict in 
the government, since Foreign Trade Minister Pertti Salolainen, 
the National Coalition Party chairman, has said that current 
levels of agricultural support ought to suffice even in a period 
of transition to the EU. 
  For his part Interior Minister Mauri Pekkarinen indicated on 
Sunday his readiness to finance the additional expense of EU 
membership by taking additional loans. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

