<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU, Norway `Approaching' Fishing Rights Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0803180294 Paris AFP in English 1740 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0803180294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Brussels, March 8 (AFP) -- The European Union 
[EU] and Norway were rapidly approaching a deal here Tuesday [8 
March] in their quarrel over fishing rights which has been 
blocking Norway's entry into the enlarging EU, diplomats said. 
  But they added that progress was slower in another dispute 
threatening to block membership for Austria, Finland and Sweden 
as well as Norway -- over how their entry would affect the 
delicate balance of power in the EU. 
  German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said he was "cautiously 
optimistic" that the EU would reach an accord with Norway later 
Tuesday over a Spanish demand for increased access to Norwegian 
cod. 
  He was speaking as the EU ministers were considering a new 
Norwegian offer to break the deadlock which has delayed 
agreement for Norway to join the 12-nation union along with the 
three other applicants on January 1. 
  Kinkel told journalists: "If we should succeed in getting a 
positive solution for Norway, I cannot imagine that the entire 
enlargement process will be blocked (by the balance of power 
dispute)." 
  Spain and Portugal are claiming the right to take about 
25,000 tonnes of cod a year out of Norwegian waters in return 
for accepting Norway into the EU -- a condition which Oslo has 
refused. 
  But a Norwegian diplomat said the EU had been offered a new 
and complicated fish catch formula which might satisfy Spain 
and "contains almost all the elements of an agreement." [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

