<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Break Down; Kinkel Blames Spain </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903124994 Berlin N-TV in German 1100 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0903124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin N-TV </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The German foreign minister went into the 
negotiations on Norway's membership of the European Union 
optimistically. Shortly before midnight, however, an annoyed 
Klaus Kinkel had to announce the breakdown of the unsuccessful 
talks. His colleagues had worked on a compromise proposal on 
the fish issue in long, tough negotiations with the Norwegians. 
The Spaniards were to be given higher catch quotas in the 
future. But Madrid was unyielding. 
  [Begin recording] [Kinkel] The failure to resolve the fish 
issue is Spain's responsibility, and to a lesser extent 
Portugal's, but basically Spain's. We had put together a 
package -- the presidency, the Commission, and the Europeans, we 
Germans in particular -- we negotiated the issue bilaterally 
with Norway. The package didn't go far enough for the 
Spaniards. Great Britain was mainly responsible for the failure 
to reach agreement on majorities as it saw no possibility for 
agreement. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Over the last few weeks the 
impression has arisen that the Spaniards are resisting Norway's 
membership in principle. Do you think this impression is 
justified? 
  [Kinkel] No, I don't think this impression is justified. The 
Spaniards want Norway to join. They have their internal 
problems with the fish issue -- we have to understand that. On 
the other hand, I didn't really understand today why they had to 
exhaust this issue in such detail. In my opinion a solution 
should have been possible. No, Spain wants them to join but it 
will get a bit more difficult now. And Spain has to move now. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

