<H3> <TI>   Spain's Solana Sees `No Progress' in EU Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0803132894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1240 GMT 8 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0803132894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "European Union: No Progress in </F>
Norwegian Membership Talks"] 
  [Text] Brussels, 8 Mar (ANSA) -- A first day of talks, 
Monday [7 March], and overnight contacts between European Union 
officials and Norwegian representatives did nothing to smooth 
out difficulties in Norway's EU membership bid, Spanish sources 
said Tuesday. 
  "There was no progress overnight in negotiations on 
fishing," 
said Spain's Foreign Minister Javier Solana. 
  The main hitch in Norway's membership talks remains demands 
from Spain and Portugal that their fishing fleets should be able 
to net 14,000 and 7,000 tonnes respectively of cod fish from 
Norwegian waters each year. Portugal, which considers cod its 
national dish, bought 40 percent of its total fish imports from 
Norway in 1993. 
  Norway has also refused to countenance demands from France 
and Ireland for limits on Norwegian fish exports. 
  The foreign ministers talks, which resumed here this 
morning, 
have also faltered over new decision-making procedures to be 
adopted when Sweden, Finland, Austria and possibly Norway join 
the Union. 
  Italy, Britain and Spain are demanding changes to the 
statute 
to make sure that small nations accounting for only small 
percentages of total EU population cannot veto decisions. 

</TEXT>

