<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Italy Bars Implementation of EU Budget Reform </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0903115294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2002 GMT 8 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0903115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "European Union: Italy Blocks Budget </F>
Citing GDP Criteria"] 
  [Text] Brussels, 8 Mar (ANSA) -- Citing "general policy 
reservations," Italy barred implementation of the European Union 
[EU] budget reform that had been agreed on at the Edinburgh 
summit of 1992, diplomatic sources said. EU foreign ministers 
failed to approve the budget reform that would base 
contributions in direct proportion to gross domestic product 
levels and in inverse proportion to VAT [value-added tax] rates. 
  Italy said its reform of the calculation by which GDP [gross 
domestic product] is calculated put it at a disadvantage in 
relation to other EU countries that have not yet carried out 
that change in the way production levels are estimated. 
  According to Italian representatives, that discrepancy could 
cost Italy 1 trillion lire yearly in EU budget contributions. 
  Italian sources also cited the outstanding dispute between 
Italy and the EU on milk quotas, arguing these could cost Italy 
between 2.5 and 5 trillion lire if quotas remain at present 
levels. Italy believes the EU has not moved quickly enough on 
agricultural reform where the Mediterranean products are 
concerned, and that further negotiations are needed on 
agro-monetary realignment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-18776 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu046__a94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-046-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
