<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Governors To Retain Current Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0803162894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1349 GMT 8 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0803162894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Central Bank Governors on Inflation, </F>
Continuity"] 
  [Text] Basel, 8 Mar (ANSA) -- European central bank 
governors will be keeping a weather eye on price rises but will 
stick to current economic policy, it was decided during their 
regular meeting in Basle, Tuesday [8 March], well-informed 
sources said. 
  Inflation seems to have been brought under control, reaching 
close to zero in France and suffering only minor hiccoughs in 
Germany, and market ups and downs have been proved nothing but 
temporary hitches in what is a mainly stable environment. 
  These elements, the sources said, prompted something akin to 
optimism amongst the European bank governors, who may now begin 
putting pressure on Germany to separate its economic policy from 
that of the United States, where recovery is already under way. 
Germany will be asked to act for itself with greater 
determination. 
  The Germans have promised not to let future decisions be 
overshadowed by January's massive growth in money supply, and 
other European nations are now looking forward to a downturn in 
interest rates, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

