<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Criticizes Reintroduction of `Super 301' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0803113794 Brussels BELGA in French 1710 GMT 7 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0803113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed MPN/JWI: "Belgium Protests `Super 301'"; as </F>
released by Brussels BELGA Database] 
  [Text] Brussels, 7 Mar (BELGA) -- Robert Urbain, Belgian 
minister for foreign trade and European affairs, has affirmed 
that he was astonished at U.S. President Bill Clinton's decision 
to reintroduce the "Super 301" procedure. 
  This unilateral measure permits the United States to take 
retaliatory measures against countries that are opening up their 
markets insufficiently to U.S. products. 
  "Although this decision has been dictated by the U.S.' vast 
trade deficit ($59.3 billion) with Japan," Robert Urbain 
continued in a press release issued in Brussels on Monday [7 
March], "the moment chosen to announce this measure is entirely 
inappropriate, since it comes just after the conclusion of the 
arduous negotiations on a GATT agreement thatwill be signed 
officially one month from now in Marrakesh." 
  Mr. Urbain said that, "without seeking to attach too much 
importance to the effects on our foreign trade caused by 
resorting to this `Super 301' weapon, which must be considered 
more as a means of dissuasion and whose reintroduction is 
certainly also motivated by domestic policy considerations," its 
use "runs totally counter to the procedures aimed at combatting 
unfair competition." 
  "Falling back on unilateralism to resolve trade conflicts 
should be avoided at all costs," the foreign trade minister 
concluded. 

</TEXT>

