<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Official Signs Crime Agreement With Estonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703185894 Hamburg DPA in German 1431 GMT 7 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0703185894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- In the future, Germany and Estonia 
want to cooperate closely in combating organized crime, 
terrorism, and other crimes. A corresponding agreement was 
signed by Eduard Lintner (Christian Social Union), parliamentary 
state secretary in the FRG Interior Ministry, and Estonian 
Interior Minister Heike Arike in Bonn on 7 March. The foci of 
joint police investigations are to be, among other things, 
drug-related crimes, forged money, and the smuggling of people, 
as well as money laundering, the smuggling of stolen cars, and 
arms trade. 
  Lintner stressed the need for ever closer police cooperation 
with the countries in East Europe and the successor states of 
the Soviet Union. The FRG has categorized them in three 
"rings," depending on their geographic location. After the 
conclusion of agreements with Poland, the Czech Republic, the 
Slovak Republic, Hungary, and Bulgaria, the treaty with Latvia 
[as received] is the first one with a country of the second 
"ring," to which, in addition to the Baltic states, Russia, 
Belarus, and Ukraine are counted. Agreements are also planned 
with the Central Asian, formerly Soviet, republics as the third 
"ring," Lintner said. "Gratifying beginnings" already exist, in 
particular with Uzbekistan, he noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

