<H3> <TI>   Bonn Makes Proposals for Allies' Departure From Berlin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0803173994 Hamburg DPA in German 1446 GMT 8 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0803173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The Federal Government has submitted 
proposals to the three former Western allies for bidding 
farewell to their troop contingents in Berlin. Government 
spokesman Dieter Vogel told this to journalists in Bonn on 
Tuesday [8 March]. For this reason, the ambassadors of France, 
Great Britain, and the United States were received in the 
chancellor's office for an exchange of information last Friday. 
  The departure is planned for September. The last contingent 
of Russian troops is to be bidden farewell already in August. 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Russian President Boris Yeltsin will 
be present at the ceremony. 
  According to Vogel, on Tuesday the Cabinet adopted the 
German-Russian treaty on mutual disaster relief, which was 
signed by Kohl in Moscow already in December 1992, and passed 
the annual disarmament report to Parliament. This report by the 
Foreign Ministry deals with Europe's political efforts for 
disarmament and arms control. The Ministry intends to comment 
on the contents in the next few days. 

</TEXT>

