<H3> <TI>   Kohl Calls For `Thrift' in 1995 Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0803170594 Hamburg DPA in German 1526 GMT 8 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0803170594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- At the Cabinet meeting on Tuesday [8 
March] Chancellor Helmut Kohl supported Finance Minister Theo 
Waigel (Christian Social Union) and called on the individual 
ministers to exercise thrift in drawing up the 1995 federal 
budget. The draft budget for next year will, however, 
"certainly no be adopted by parliament before the Bundestag 
elections (16 October)," government spokesman Dieter Vogel 
announced after the Cabinet meeting. 
  However, the Federal Government will stick to the usual 
dates 
and pass the draft budget in the Cabinet at the end of June. 
The basis are the overall economic basic data, which have to be 
presented this April, and the next tax estimate in May. 
  Vogel added: "The Cabinet is aware of the fact that extreme 
thrift in budget policy and in the demands of the individual 
ministries is necessary also for 1995." The chancellor did "not 
leave any doubt" as to this necessity. The Cabinet members 
"will take this into account when working out their plans for 
1995," Vogel said. 

</TEXT>

