<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   GDP in Eastern Germany Increases in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0903100694 Hamburg DPA in German 0737 GMT 9 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0903100694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wiesbaden (DPA) -- In 1993, the economic performance 
in eastern Germany measured by the GDP rose by 7.1 percent in 
real terms compared with the year before. Thus, the economic 
growth in the new laender and in the former East Berlin was 0.8 
percentage points above the preliminary value published in 
January. This was announced by the Federal Statistical Office 
in Wiesbaden on Wednesday [9 March]. During the second half of 
1993, the GDP rose by 7.4 percent compared with the second half 
of 1992. During this period it amounted to about 149 billion 
German marks. As a result, eastern Germany has a share of 9.2 
percent in the overall German economic performance. 

</TEXT>

