<H3> <TI>   Ciampi Sees No Change in Economic Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0703154394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1400 GMT 7 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0703154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ciampi Sees No Change in Future </F>
Economic Policy"] 
  [Text] Naples, 7 Mar (ANSA) -- The next government will 
have no choice but to follow the same path and seek the same 
objectives as the current executive in matters of economic 
policy, even if differences can exist on the tools to achieve 
the same objectives, Italian Premier Carlo Azeglio Ciampi said 
here on Monday [7 March]. 
  Speaking at the presentation of next July's summit here of 
the West's group of seven most industrialised countries (G-7), 
Ciampi also paid attention to last week's turbulence on 
international markets and observed that it had been "an 
excessive reaction" to the American decision to slightly 
increase short-term interest rates. The long-time Bank of Italy 
governor added how the same criteria for rates did not apply to 
both Europe and the United States. 
  Turning his attention to Italy's trade balance, premier 
Ciampi forecast how it will improve this year even over the 13 
trillion lire (7.7 billion dollars) assets posted for 1993. 
  He also down-played the reduced tax revenue reported last 
week, stating how the difference between forecast and intake had 
been modest and determined by a dip in the gross domestic 
product. 

</TEXT>

