<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Businessmen Support Rightist Alliance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0803161294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1308 GMT 8 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0803161294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Small-Medium Businessmen Leaning </F>
Right, Poll Shows"] 
  [Text] Milan, 8 Mar (ANSA) -- Silvio Berlusconi and his Go 
Italy [Forza Italia] movement are favored by a relative majority 
of artisans and small- and medium-sized activity businessmen, 
followed by Mario Segni and his Pact for Italy, according to a 
poll to be published in the next edition of the "SRL" magazine, 
to be distributed with the economic daily ITALIA OGGI. 
  The poll showed how Berlusconi won the support of 32 percent 
of those interviewed, followed by Segni with 24.5 percent and 
the People's Party [Italian Popular Party], the ex-Christian 
Democrats, with 12.9 percent and liberals with 8 percent, while 
the Northern League was favored by only 6 percent of those 
quizzed and the rightists of National Alliance, headed by the 
neo-fascist MSI, came in at 2.5 percent. 
  The poll also asked sector organizations to list the 
priorities and coming in first was a rationalization of the 
taxation system for businesses, a general reduction in labor 
costs and greater flexibility for hiring and firing. 

</TEXT>

