<H3> <TI>   Business Says 1993 Labor Accord Model for G-7 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0903115094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1939 GMT 8 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0903115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Italy's Cost of Labor Accord a Model </F>
for G-7, Say Unions, Management"] 
  [Text] Rome, 8 Mar (ANSA) -- Italy's trade unions and 
business owners think last summer's hard-fought cost of labor 
agreement should be a model for other Group of Seven countries 
fighting unemployment, and are asking the government to say so 
at the upcoming G-7 summit in Detroit. 
  Confindustria [General Confederation of Italian Industry], 
the manufacturer's association, and the three major trade 
federations CGIL [Italian General Confederation of Labor], CISL 
[Italian Confederation of Trade Unions] and UIL [Italian 
Federation of Trade Unions], met today with Prime Minister 
Ciampi, Treasury Minister Piero Barucci and Labor Minister Gino 
Giugni in preparation for that international meeting on 
employment scheduled for March 14-15. 
  "We think last July's agreement should be highlighted as a 
model for a bargaining agreement that involves labor, management 
and the government," said Confindustria director general 
Innocenzo Cipolletta. 
  Cipolletta, who attended today's meeting along with the vice 
president of the association Carlo Callieri, asked the 
government to urge the G-7 to focus on the following issues: 
stimulation of demand, development policy, training policy, and 
a more flexible labor market. 
  Antonio Lettieri, in charge of international relations for 
CGIL, the largest of Italy's three trade union federations, 
asked the government to press for "the introduction of a `social 
clause' in international trade accords that would provide a 
floor of protection for workers rights" in those G-7 talks. 

</TEXT>

