<H3> <TI>   Royal Marines To Train Baltic Peacekeeping Battalion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803192594 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1507 GMT 8 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0803192594 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Stephen Alderman, PRESS ASSOCIATION parliamentary staff] </F>
  [Text] Britain's Royal Marines are to help train a new 
Baltic peacekeeping battalion, Defence Secretary Malcolm Rifkind 
announced in the Commons today. 
  He disclosed that he had today formally agreed that the UK 
would contribute to the training of a Baltic joint peacekeeping 
battalion composed of contingents from Lithuania, Latvia and 
Estonia. 
  This was part of a phased multi-national programme of 
assistance, Mr Rifkind said at question time. 
  He added: "The UK's contribution will be led by the Royal 
Marines who will provide individual and company level training." 
  A Defence Ministry statement said the move followed a recent 
meeting at which the defence ministers of the three Baltic 
states indicated their wish to accept UK and Nordic offers of 
assistance. 
  The statement added: "The UK fully supports the Baltic 
states' intention to form a joint peacekeeping battalion and 
welcomes the prospect that, once established and trained, the 
battalion would be available for UN peacekeeping duties. 
  ``This is an important venture, both politically and 
militarily, and provides a tangible demonstration of 
outward-looking Baltic cooperation, and an opportunity to 
further consolidate and build on the excellent progress already 
made in strengthening political and military relations between 
the UK and the Baltic States.'' 
  The precise nature of assistance was now being examined by 
experts and officials would meet later this month in Copenhagen 
to agree the next stages, the statement added. 

</TEXT>

