<H3> <TI>   Politics, Finance Challenge Bundeswehr in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803144294 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1243 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0803144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- The framework conditions for 
the Bundeswehr are worse, according to Alfred Biehle, the 
Bundestag commissioner for the armed forces. This applied in 
particular to the financial framework, Biehle said, as he 
presented his annual report for 1993 to journalists in Bonn 
today. Politics had left the soldiers uncertain about how much 
money the Bundeswehr would finally have at its disposal. There 
was also still no constitutional consensus on foreign missions 
by the Bundeswehr. 
  With regard to the German UN missions in Somalia and 
Cambodia, the Christian Social Union politician added that 
"despite all the problems in the starting up period," an 
"excellent service" had been provided. Given the ever growing 
spectrum of tasks and the reductions in money, however, the 
Bundeswehr was being forced into an "involuntary balancing act." 
This had had "extremely negative" effects on the morale and the 
confidence of the soldiers. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

