<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel: Germany To `Help Mediate' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903143194 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1247 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0903143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel has called on Russia to adhere to the agreed August 
deadline for withdrawing its troops from the Baltic states. 
This was an important confidence-building measure for the 
region and for security throughout Europe, Kinkel said on 
Wednesday [9 March] at a joint news conference with his 
counterparts from Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania in Bonn. 
Germany did not want to take on an "official role as 
intermediary" between Russia and the Baltics, but it did want to 
"help mediate." At the same time, Kinkel reaffirmed German 
support for the efforts of the Baltic states to be accepted 
gradually into the European Union [EU] and the Atlantic defense 
alliance. 
  Lithuanian Foreign Minister Povilas Gylys expressed the 
expectation that the negotiations on association with the EU 
would begin in the second half of 1994 and be concluded at the 
beginning of next year. On the situation of the Russian 
minority in the Baltic states, Estonian Foreign Minister Juri 
Luik said that even foreign organizations had found no evidence 
of human rights violations. Problems arose mainly on practical 
issues concerning the integration of Russian citizens. 

</TEXT>

