<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bundesbank To Achieve Money Supply Objective </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0803175094 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
8 Mar 94 p 13 </F>

<F P=103> AU0803175094 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["gb."-initialed report: "Money Supply Objective </F>
Achievable"] 
  [Text] Frankfurt, 7 March -- Despite the great expansion 
of the money supply in January (annual rate: 20.6 percent), 
Johann Wilhelm Gaddum, vice president of the German Bundesbank, 
believes that the Bundesbank will still achieve its money supply 
objective for 1994. For the fourth quarter of the year, its 
target is a 4 to 6 percent increase in the money supply compared 
to the fourth quarter of 1993. In an interview with FRANKFURTER 
ALLGEMEINE, Gaddum said a preliminary decision in this 
connection would probably be made in the coming months. For the 
longer term, the framework conditions speak for a slower 
expansion of the money supply. In this connection, Gaddum 
mentioned the less expansive financial policy, wage agreements 
that are compatible with stability, and the absence of tension 
on the foreign currency markets. "There is no reason to 
exaggerate nervousness," Gaddum said. For the Bundesbank there 
is no reason right now to abandon the monetary policy, which is 
guided by a long-term perspective, or to change its course as 
far as monetary policy is concerned. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

