<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Slight Recovery Reported in Eastern Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903093894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0619 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0903093894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- GDP in the states of former 
East Germany increased by an average 7.1 percent in real terms 
in 1993, and thus rose by more than had been expected. This was 
announced by the Federal Economics Ministry in Bonn today. At 
7.4 percent in the second half of the year, it grew clearly more 
than in the first half of the year. Gross domestic product per 
worker in the states of former East Germany reached around 46 
percent of the Western level last year. 
  In the view of Federal Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt, 
the Federal Statistical Office's data confirm that there has 
been a high rate of growth in eastern Germany over the past two 
years. Following a temporary deceleration, the economic catching 
up process evidently has started to accelerate again somewhat. 
However, this could not yet be described as a self-sustaining 
recovery in the states of former East Germany. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

