<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   West Turns `Blind Eye' to PRC Political Suppression </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0803205094 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
5 Mar 94 p 12 </F>

<F P=103> AU0803205094 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Nt."-initialed commentary: "Blind Eye"] </F>
  [Text] With the arrest of several prominent opposition 
members, the Chinese Government has shown what it thinks of 
Western criticism: nothing. Shortly before a visit by the U.S. 
secretary of state to Beijing, this appears to be a challenge. 
The United States has again and again threatened to withdraw 
the most-favored-nation status from China, but that is usually 
it. The Chinese market is too enticing. Europeans are behaving 
in a similar way. It has been argued that the closer the 
economic ties, the greater the chances for loosening up the 
rigid political system in China. Time and again, this has 
proved to be wrong. Nevertheless, the West is sticking to this 
illusionary policy. Even this time, officials will find an 
excuse. Maybe the dissidents will be released again after the 
People's Congress, due to open next week and which must not be 
disturbed by requests for more democracy. Maybe. At any rate, 
for the sake of economic interests, the West will again and 
again turn a blind eye to political suppression in China, and 
even more so in Tibet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

