<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Forged Dollars Distributed to Russia Via Estonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803122194 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1100 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0803122194 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dollars and 100-crown bills forged in Finland have 
been distributed in Russia via Estonia. Two Finnish men have 
been imprisoned in Estonia on remand for 10 months for 
distributing forged money. They were arrested in southern 
Estonia close to the Russian border in April just under a year 
ago together with two Estonians and a load of forged money. At 
that time the men were carrying 6,500 forged 20-dollar bills as 
well as 48 100-dollar bills. The Finnish police went to Estonia 
to establish that the dollars came from the same series as over 
100 kg of forged dollars previously confiscated in Finland. The 
value of these printed dollars was several million markkas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-18861 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu046_n_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-046 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   World War II Chemical Weapons Dumped in Baltic Sea </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803212494 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1900 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0803212494 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to a report received by the Baltic Sea 
Marine Protection Commission, at least 40,000 tonnes of chemical 
weapons and ammunition from World War II were dumped into the 
Baltic Sea. Approximately 13,000 tonnes of this is war 
chemicals. The dumping continued until the end of 1947. In 
addition, the former East Germany dumped 200 tonnes of 
ammunition in the Baltic Sea during the 1950's. The Protection 
Commission is still awaiting more information from Russia about 
the destruction of chemical weapons. According to the report, 
known dumping sites in the Baltic Sea are situated on the 
southeastern side of Gotland, on the eastern side of Bornholm, 
and in the Little Belt in the Danish straits. The report urges 
the Protection Commission to issue general rules for fishermen 
in case chemical weapons get entangled in their catching 
equipment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

