<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kliridhis Receives U.S. Special Coordinator </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0803142194 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1130 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0803142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Robert Lamb, U.S. State Department special 
coordinator on Cyprus who is in Nicosia, today began contacts in 
the third round of the proximity talks on the 
confidence-building measures. This morning Lamb had a one-hour 
meeting with President Glavkos Kliridhis. Lamb described the 
meeting with Kliridhis as a very useful one during which they 
discussed details related to the current phase of the talks. 
  Asked whether he brings new ideas, Lamb said that the United 
Nations is working hard to make sure that the interests of both 
sides are protected. I do not think, he said, that there is a 
need for new ideas at the present stage. The U.S. special 
coordinator said that he repeated to President Kliridhis the US 
conviction that the confidence-building measures are positive 
and useful and create the opportunity for progress. 
  Replying to other questions, Lamb said that during this 
current phase the two sides will voice their doubts on how the 
issues of Famagusta and Nicosia Airport will work out. He 
described the reservations expressed as logical. He said that 
the process is difficult but very important. Lamb also stressed 
that there is a lot of skepticism on both sides as to whether 
the other side is willing to proceed. However, he added, the 
leadership of both sides have enough perception to be able to 
see that these efforts can lead to an acceptable final 
settlement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

