<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Spokesman on Butrus-Ghali's Report </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0803150694 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1130 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0803150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Government Spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis has said 
that the Cyprus Government is evaluating the UN secretary 
general's report, the first part of which describes the 
developments since his last report, issued on 22 November 1993. 
In the second part of his report, Kasoulidhis added, the 
secretary general proceeds with an analysis of the problems that 
have arisen and the key points of which should be agreed upon by 
both sides, as they constitute the substance of the current 
phase of the proximity talks on the confidence-building 
measures. The government spokesman said that the UN 
Secretariat's approach is evident on some issues. Our side, has 
outlined its views, he continued, and it reserves the right to 
agree or disagree at the negotiating table. Kasoulidhis said 
that in the third part of the report the UN secretary general 
presents some notes related with the way the proximity talks 
will proceed starting tomorrow, the logical timeframe for 
expanding the talks, and the importance he attaches to the 
prospect of concluding an agreement, or not. 
  Asked to comment on an observation that the secretary 
general's report takes a clear stance on issues about which our 
side has expressed disagreement, especially on the issues of 
turning over sovereignty over Nicosia International Airport and 
free use of it by Turkish Cypriots with their own travel 
documents, the spokesman said that he can not comment on issues 
under discussion at the negotiating table. Kasoulidhis added 
that our side sees in the report some approaches by the 
secretary general that are closer to our side and others that 
differ from our side's positions. Replying to a question, the 
spokesman said setting the end of March as the timeframe is 
reasonable to reach agreements on the seven major issues. 

</TEXT>

