<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Calls For UNPROFOR Reinforcements in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0803133494 Brussels BELGA in French 2340 GMT 7 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0803133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed LVE: "The Twelve Call For UNPROFOR </F>
Reinforcements"] 
  [Text] Brussels, 7 Mar (BELGA) -- European Union (EU) 
foreign ministers stressed on Monday evening [7 March] the need 
for reinforcements for the UN Protection Forces (UNPROFOR) in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, thus responding favorably to an appeal by 
France. 
  They also stressed the importance of the more active role 
now 
played by the United States and Russia in bringing peace to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, while pointing out that the EU cannot allow 
itself to be reduced to playing an "inferior role," in the words 
of Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias, whose country holds 
the EU presidency until 30 June. 
  The Twelve gave their backing to French Foreign Minister 
Alain Juppe, who had called upon the Twelve and others, notably 
the United States, to send UNPROFOR reinforcements to Bosnia. 
  Mr. Papoulias refused to say, however, if any of them had 
indicated their willingness to participate in the effort deemed 
necessary. His French colleague indicated that France, which 
has the largest contingent of blue helmets in the area, had 
"done its duty." 
  France also called upon its European partners to reintegrate 
the Serbs in the peace process. "You cannot make peace between 
two in a three-sided conflict," said Mr. Juppe, with reference 
to the accord between the Croats and the Muslims on creating a 
federation involving these two sides in Bosnia. 
  He went on to propose a meeting between the Europeans, the 
Russians, and the Americans in order to achieve peace. 
  Mr. Papoulias went no further than to say that the Twelve 
"were interested" in the role played by the United States and 
Russia in the peace process, but still supported the EU's peace 
plan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

