<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spain To Reply `Symbolically' to Blue Helmets Request </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903203894 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 1900 GMT 
9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0903203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Spain will say yes to the UN request for more 
blue helmets for Bosnia, but it will do so symbolically. This 
was announced this afternoon by Foreign Minister Javier Solana, 
who met with his Portuguese counterpart. The Spanish and 
Portuguese foreign ministers spoke about the European Union 
enlargement and both defend the same interests. They hope that 
Norway will change its stance on fishing. Over to Pedro 
Fernandez Cespedes. 
  [Fernandez Cespedes] Despite yesterday's attack on the 
Spanish Aviocar over Croatia, the government will not only keep 
up its commitment in Bosnia-Herzegovina, but is already studying 
the possibility of increasing our presence in the area, albeit 
symbolically. 
  While waiting for the Army chief of staff's report, Minister 
Solana adds another company of soldiers to the technicians the 
defense minister promised yesterday. 
  [Begin Solana recording] He was speaking about the 
possibility of sending some radar-type material along with 
technicians, that would be some 30 people or something like 
that. And the Ministry of Defense is considering the 
possibility of maybe sending a company of soldiers. That would 
be it. 
  I have to repeat that Spain is fulfilling its obligations. 
It is doing so generously, efficiently. [end recording] 
  [Fernandez Cespedes] Minister Solana is sure that 
yesterday's 
attack on the Spanish Aviocar will get an adequate answer from 
the international community. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

