<H3> <TI>   Twelve Advocate Reinforcing UNPROFOR in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1003103894 Brussels EUROPE in English 8 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1003103894 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels EUROPE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Twelve Call For a Reinforcement of </F>
UNPROFOR"; as released by Brussels TEXTLINE database] 
  [Text] At their debate on Monday [7 March] evening on 
former Yugoslavia under Common Foreign and Security Policy, the 
foreign ministers of the Twelve insisted on the need to 
reinforce United Nations Protection Force (UNPROFOR) troops in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. France first and foremost, speaking through 
Foreign Minister Alain Juppe, had urged in favour of increasing 
the number of blue helmets in Bosnia. The French view is that 
reinforcements should be provided by the Twelve but also by the 
United States. Speaking to the press, Mr. Papoulias, however, 
refused to say whether any of the other EC countries have so far 
stated their willingness to actively participate in this further 
effort considered necessary. Mr. Juppe, for his part, pointed 
out that France (which already has the largest contingent of 
blue helmets) had "done its duty." The French Minister, 
moreover, launched an appeal to his European partners to 
reintegrate the Serbs into the peace process. "Peace will not 
be achieved with two parties when there are three in the 
conflict," he said speaking of the recent agreement reached 
between Croats and Muslims on the creation of a two-sided 
federation in Bosnia. The Twelve also stressed the growing 
importance of the role henceforth played by the United States 
and Russia in bringing peace to Bosnia while recalling that the 
European Union could not see itself reduced to an "inferior 
role" as Mr. Papoulias had stated, before going on to say that 
the EC is "interested" in strengthened diplomatic activity by 
the United States and Russia in the peace process, "but it still 
wishes to keep to its peace plan." 

</TEXT>

