<H3> <TI>   Kohl Blames London, Madrid for Failure of EU Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0903140294 Hamburg DPA in German 1240 GMT 9 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0903140294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- FRG Chancellor Helmut Kohl has blamed 
Spain and Great Britain for the preliminary failure of Norway's 
negotiations for membership in the European Union [EU]. It is 
"completely inexplicable" for the Federal Government and him 
personally that, in view of the outstanding political importance 
of this question for Europe, member countries have not endorsed 
the consensus, the chancellor stated in Bonn on Wednesday [9 
March]. 
  In the question of fishery, a package that had exactly taken 
Madrid's interests into account was presented. "I hope that 
Spain will endorse this balanced proposal." In the controversy 
over the blocking minority, the EU presidency presented a 
"reasonable proposal." He hopes that Great Britain will still 
agree to it. According to Kohl, the Federal Government sticks to 
the objective of admiting all four countries -- Austria, Sweden, 
Finland, and Norway -- to the European Union in January 1995. 
He appealed to the still hesitant member countries to clear the 
road for the conclusion of the negotiations for membership now. 

</TEXT>

