<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stoiber Accuses Kinkel of `Narrow-Minded Nationalism' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0903144994 Hamburg DPA in German 1225 GMT 9 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0903144994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels -- Bavaria's Minister President Edmund 
Stoiber (Christian Social Union) has accused Foreign Minister 
Klaus Kinkel (Free Democratic Party) of "narrow-minded 
nationalism" in European policies. As an example, he cited the 
discussion about the bugging of private residences, which is 
possible in all other European countries. "In Brussels, our 
great Europeans suddenly turn into completely narrow-minded 
people who insist on national competences," Stoiber stressed at 
a news conference in Brussels today, referring to the negative 
attitude of the Free Democratic Party on the issue of the 
bugging campaign. 
  Stoiber accused Kinkel of preventing a standardization of 
the 
export regulations for goods that can be used for military and 
civilian purposes. Germany is the only country to reject that. 
Thus, there is the danger that German industry might transfer 
its activities to other countries of the European Union. 
  A corresponding guideline for the so-called dual-use goods 
is 
currently under discussion. Since Germany has the strictest 
export regulations within the European Union for such products, 
Bonn insist on relative strict export regulations but is ready 
for concessions vis-a-vis other countries, experts have stated. 

</TEXT>

