<H3> <TI>   IMF: Italy Needs Further Budget Adjustments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0903141894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1225 GMT 9 
Mar 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0903141894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "IMF's Russo Says Italy Needs Further </F>
Budget Trims"] 
  [Text] Rome, 9 Mar (ANSA) -- Whoever wins the elections 
will need to carry out further adjustments to correct overruns 
in public spending, said Massimo Russo, the International 
Monetary Fund's chief for Europe, in the course of an interview 
on GR2 radio [second channel radio news]. 
  "We said in December that very likely the budget objectives 
for 1994 would not be met and that new measures would have to be 
taken within the year," said Russo. "We are now confirming that 
opinion, which is widely shared," he said. 
  He also said he believed the elections were weighing on 
Italy's economy, and that "political uncertainties have to be 
clarified before a full-scale recovery can take place." 
  "The U.S. recovery reflects the fact that recession began 
there first and now the country is recovering. The rate of 
recovery is good but not exceptional; for Europe the timing is 
slower," Russo said. 
  Italy's gross domestic product should grow 1-1.1 percent, 
"as 
predicted in December," he added. 

</TEXT>

