<H3> <TI>   Government Plans To Boost Forces in Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0903140494 Paris AFP in English 1343 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0903140494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 9 (AFP) -- France plans a rapid boost 
to its forces in Sarajevo by redeploying a battalion of 800 men 
in the UN Protection Force [UNPROFOR], Foreign Ministry 
spokesman Richard Duque said here Wednesday [9 March]. 
  The move was being made as a matter of urgency to help 
implement a Security Council resolution on restoring essential 
public services in the Bosnian capital, he said. 
  France has more than 6,000 troops in former Yugoslavia, 
forming the largest UNPROFOR contingent. Half are in Bosnia, 
including 2,400 at Sarajevo. 
  The redeployment to strengthen the French units in and 
around 
Sarajevo was also announced by government spokesman Nicolas 
Sarkozy after the weekly cabinet meeting. 
  He made the point that it was not a question of increasing 
France's UNPROFOR strength but of carrying out a redeployment. 
  French troops in Sarajevo meanwhile cleared away the last of 
the landmines and other defences dug in in 22 months of war at 
the Brotherhood and Unity bridge linking the Serb district of 
Grbavica to the rest of the city. 
  The French moved in a month ago when the current ceasefire 
took effect. The bridge still remains out of bounds to 
civilians however, in the absence of a political agreement 
between Bosnians and Serbs on restoring normal traffic. 

</TEXT>

