<H3> <TI>   Works To Settle Oil Dispute </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903200294 Paris Radio France International in French 1830 
GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0903200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The president of the Congolese Republic is 
continuing his high-level political talks in Paris. Pascal 
Lissouba went to see Prime Minister Edouard Balladur. Yesterday 
he was received by President Mitterrand. He also had talks with 
Michel Roussin, the minister of cooperation. To sum up for us 
so far on Pascal Lissouba's visit to Paris, here is Monique Mas: 
  [Mas] Pascal Lissouba has decided to turn the page on the 
Franco-Congolese quarrel. He hopes that French severity was 
perhaps the expression of the fact that it had entertained too 
high hopes of him, and the Congolese president is stressing that 
he has already taken a first step by settling the oil dispute to 
the benefit of French interests and to the detriment of the 
American Oxy oil company. He also denies having tried to play 
on Franco-American rivalries. In Lissouba's view, the Cold War 
is over anyway, and no one is interested in Africa any more. 
  Nevertheless, Congo greatly misses its oil revenue. With a 
70 percent debt to France [as heard], Lissouba's predecessor had 
obtained advances from the French oil company Elf, and Congolese 
oil is mortgaged until about 2010. The coffers are empty, but 
President Lissouba has no choice but to rise to the challenge 
both economically and as far as domestic politics are concerned. 
Having got his fingers burned by his first experiment with a 
government with 60 percent of the ministers coming from the 
opposition, he is now counting on decentralization to ensure 
civil peace. 
  [Announcer] Congolese students in Paris invaded the premises 
of their embassy this morning to protest at the nonpayment of 
their scholarships for 16 months. 

</TEXT>

