<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Main Greenland Bank Returns to Profit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94EN0233D Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 16 Feb 94 
p 6 </F>

<F P=103> 94EN0233D </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Danish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [RITZAUS BUREAU (RB) report: "Greenland Surplus"] </F>
  [Text] In spite of the fishing crisis and a generally low 
level of economic activity in Greenland, the Greenland Bank had 
a surplus of 42.1 million kroner in 1993 compared with a deficit 
of 6.9 million the year before. This is due primarily to falling 
interest rates that led to an exchange rate profit on bonds. The 
exchange rate loss of 22.2 million kroner in 1992 changed to a 
surplus of 32.6 million kroner in 1992. Greenland Bank's general 
banking operations were almost unchanged in relation to 1992. 
However, net interest and fee income rose from 74.5 million to 
83.8 million kroner. Losses and set-asides amounted to 8.2 
million kroner in 1993 -- almost the same as in 1992. 

</TEXT>

