<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Battalion Available for UN Bosnia Mission </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1003113294 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1100 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1003113294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New York, Mar. 10 (A.A.) -- Turkey informed the 
United Nations that it was ready to send 1,000 soldiers to the 
UN Forces in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Turkey's permanent representative at the United Nations Inal 
Batu conveyed Turkey's proposal during a meeting in New York, of 
representatives of countries which are expected to send troops 
to the region. 
  Speaking at the second session of the meeting on Wednesday 
[9 
March], Ambassador Batu said that Turkey was ready to take part 
in the peace keeping forces by volunteering a batallion. 
  After the meeting Batu told the Anatolian News Agency that 
the proposal involving 1,000 soldiers constituted one-fourth of 
the total number of soldiers proposed by the other countries. 

</TEXT>

