<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Warned Against Sending Troops to Azerbaijan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1003100294 Istanbul HURRIYET in Turkish 8 Mar 94 p 16 </F>
<F P=103> NC1003100294 </F>
<F P=104>  Istanbul HURRIYET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Selin Caglayan: "Ankara Challenges Russia on </F>
Azerbaijan"] 
  [Text] Turkey has categorically warned Russia that it 
cannot unilaterallly deploy troops in Azerbaijan. HURRIYET has 
ascertained that Bilgin Unan, deputy under secretary at the 
Turkish Foreign Ministry, informed Russian officials in Moscow 
last week that the peacekeeping force to be deployed in 
Azerbaijan must be established by international units. He said: 
"Russia cannot be the only country to deploy troops in 
Azerbaijan. Turkey will also deploy its troops if Russia sends 
its military forces to that republic." 
  Stressing that Turkey will accept no solution that will 
allow 
Armenian forces to be present in Azerbaijan, Unan reiterated 
Ankara's view that the solution must come within the framework 
of the CSCE Minsk Group's effort. Russian officials have 
insisted that their country's plan must also be effected in 
parallel with the Minsk Group's effort. Unan responded by 
saying that a comprehensive solution must be found to resolve 
the dispute. 
  According to the Turkish officials' impression, Russia will 
keep trying to impose Moscow's plan on the Baku administration. 
The plan calls for the deployment of Russia's troops in 
Azerbaijan. It has been ascertained that Ankara, considering 
the possibility of President Aliyev agreeing to Russia's plan, 
regards the Azerbaijani People's Front and former President 
Abulfaz Elchibey as a second force guaranteeing opposition in 
that republic to Moscow's intention. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

